
also called " Production Planning & Execution " 

Do: create first Main Item then create raw materials as a to create that Main item


####################################################################################################################################################################################

	


‚úÖ Doctypes Understanding



1. Bill of Materials (BOM) ----

üîπ Purpose / Role: 

- The Bill of Materials defines the recipe or blueprint for manufacturing a product.
- It lists which raw materials, in what quantity, and what operations are needed to make one finished item.
- It acts as the foundation for all manufacturing activities ‚Äî like production planning, costing, and work orders.



üîπ Real-World Example (Laptop Manufacturing)
Let‚Äôs say your company manufactures Laptops.

To make 1 Laptop, you need: 1 Motherboard, 1 Screen, 1 Keyboard, 1 Battery, 1 Laptop Body


- In ERPNext, you create a Bill of Materials for the item Laptop.
- This BOM will define all these raw materials (and optionally operations like ‚ÄúAssemble Components‚Äù, ‚ÄúInstall OS‚Äù, ‚ÄúFinal Testing‚Äù).

- Later, when you create a Work Order, ERPNext will use this BOM to know what materials to consume and how many units to produce.

‚û°Ô∏è BOM = Recipe for making your Laptop.



--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------


2. Production Plan


üîπ Purpose / Role :

- A Production Plan helps you organize and schedule manufacturing based on upcoming sales or material demands.
- It‚Äôs used when you need to produce multiple finished goods or plan production for a specific period ‚Äî ensuring enough raw materials and capacity are available.

It basically answers the question: ‚ÄúWhat items should we manufacture, in what quantity, and when?‚Äù



üîπ Real-World Example (Laptop Manufacturing)

- Your company receives multiple sales orders for 100 Laptops next month.
- Instead of creating Work Orders one by one, you create a Production Plan for 100 Laptops.

ERPNext then:

- Automatically checks the Bill of Materials (BOM) of the Laptop.
- Calculates how many raw materials (like motherboards, screens, batteries, etc.) are required.
- Suggests creating Material Requests if stock is short.
- Generates Work Orders in bulk to manage production efficiently.



‚û°Ô∏è Production Plan = Big picture manufacturing schedule that ensures you have enough materials and resources to make your Laptops on time.




--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------



3. Work Order

üîπ Purpose / Role :

- A Work Order represents the actual production job ‚Äî it‚Äôs a detailed instruction to manufacture a specific quantity of a finished item using a selected BOM.
- It tracks the entire process from starting production to consuming materials and creating the finished goods.

Think of it as the execution document in the manufacturing process.



üîπ Real-World Example (Laptop Manufacturing)

- After finalizing the Production Plan for 100 Laptops, you create a Work Order for, say, 50 Laptops first.



This Work Order:
- Refers to the Laptop BOM (recipe).
- Reserves required materials ‚Äî like 50 motherboards, 50 screens, etc.
- Tells the shop floor team to start assembly.
- Tracks stages like Assembly, Quality Check, and Completion.
- Finally allows you to manufacture and update stock of 50 finished Laptops.


‚û°Ô∏è Work Order = The actual factory instruction that turns the BOM plan into real, physical Laptops.



--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------


4. Operation

üîπ Purpose / Role

- An Operation defines a specific step or task in the manufacturing process ‚Äî like assembling parts, testing, or packaging.
- Each operation represents a work activity that takes time, cost, and manpower, and can be assigned to a workstation.

It‚Äôs used inside the BOM and Work Orders to calculate time and cost more accurately.




üîπ Real-World Example (Laptop Manufacturing)

In your Laptop production process, there are several stages involved, such as:

1. Assemble Components ‚Äì Fitting motherboard, battery, and screen into the laptop body.
2. Software Installation ‚Äì Installing the operating system and required drivers.
3. Quality Testing ‚Äì Checking display, keyboard, and performance.
4. Packaging ‚Äì Boxing and labeling the final product.

Each of these stages is an Operation.

You‚Äôll define them in ERPNext, so when a Work Order is created, ERPNext knows what steps to follow and can calculate total operation time and cost.



‚û°Ô∏è Operation = Step-by-step activity that transforms raw materials into the finished Laptop.



--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------


5. Workstation Type

- A Workstation Type represents a category or class of workstations that perform similar kinds of operations.
- It helps standardize and organize your manufacturing setup ‚Äî especially when you have multiple workstations doing the same type of job.

You can set default settings (like hourly rate, energy cost, capacity, etc.) at the Workstation Type level, and then individual workstations can inherit those properties.


üîπ Real-World Example (Laptop Manufacturing)
- In your Laptop factory, you might have multiple Assembly Tables or Testing Benches:

Workstation Type: Assembly Table ‚Üí for assembling components.
Workstation Type: Testing Bench ‚Üí for performing quality tests.
Workstation Type: Packaging Unit ‚Üí for packing the finished Laptops.

So instead of defining rates and capacity for each individual workstation separately, you can define them once in Workstation Type and then assign that type to multiple workstations.




‚û°Ô∏è Workstation Type = Template or category used to group similar workstations in your Laptop production line.



--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------


6. Workstation

üîπ Purpose / Role

- A Workstation represents the physical place or machine where a specific operation is performed in the manufacturing process.
- It helps track where the work happens, how much time and cost it takes, and what its capacity is.

Each workstation belongs to a Workstation Type and can be linked to multiple Operations in the BOM.




üîπ Real-World Example (Laptop Manufacturing)
- In your Laptop factory, you have multiple physical setups where operations take place:

Workstation 1: Assembly Table A ‚Üí used for assembling laptop components
Workstation 2: Testing Bench 1 ‚Üí used for performing hardware and software tests
Workstation 3: Packaging Unit 2 ‚Üí used for final packing

When a Work Order is executed, ERPNext uses these workstations to:
- Allocate each Operation (like assembly or testing) to the right place
- Track how long each operation takes
- Calculate production cost based on workstation rate and time used



‚û°Ô∏è Workstation = Actual place or equipment where a specific Laptop manufacturing step physically happens.




--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------


7. Routing


üîπ Purpose / Role

- A Routing defines the sequence of operations needed to manufacture an item ‚Äî in other words, it tells ‚Äúwhich operations happen, in what order, and where.‚Äù
- It connects Operations and Workstations together to create a complete production flow.

When you attach a Routing to a BOM, ERPNext knows exactly how the manufacturing will progress ‚Äî from the first step to the last.



üîπ Real-World Example (Laptop Manufacturing)

For your Laptop, the manufacturing process goes through several steps:

1. Assemble Components ‚Üí done at Assembly Table A
2. Software Installation ‚Üí done at Software Setup Station
3. Quality Testing ‚Üí done at Testing Bench 1
4. Packaging ‚Üí done at Packaging Unit 2

You can define all these steps in one Routing called Laptop Production Routing.
Then, when you create the BOM for Laptop, you link this Routing so ERPNext knows the order of operations and the workstations to use.


‚û°Ô∏è Routing = The roadmap or workflow showing how the Laptop moves through different operations and workstations during manufacturing.



--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------



8. Stock Entry ( Material Transfer for Manufacture )

- Material Transfer for Manufacture is a type of Stock Entry used to move raw materials from the main warehouse (or stores) to the production floor/workstation location 
  before starting manufacturing.
- It ensures that all required components are available where production actually happens.

It doesn‚Äôt consume or produce anything yet ‚Äî it‚Äôs just a transfer step in the manufacturing flow.




Real-World Example (Laptop Manufacturing)

- Your store has raw materials like:
100 Motherboards
100 Screens
100 Keyboards
100 Batteries

- Now, a Work Order is created to manufacture 50 Laptops.

- Before starting assembly, you need to send materials from the Main Warehouse to the Assembly Area.

So you create a Stock Entry of type ‚ÄúMaterial Transfer for Manufacture‚Äù that moves:
- 50 Motherboards
- 50 Screens
- 50 Keyboards
- 50 Batteries 
      ‚Ä¶to the workstation‚Äôs location.

Once the materials reach the production area, actual assembly (manufacturing) can begin.



‚û°Ô∏è Material Transfer for Manufacture = Moving raw materials from the main store to the production floor before Laptop assembly starts.


--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------


9. Job Card

- A Job Card represents the actual work record for a specific operation in the manufacturing process.
- It tracks who performed the task, at which workstation, how long it took, and how much quantity was completed.

It‚Äôs created automatically (or manually) from a Work Order, based on the operations defined in its BOM or Routing.



üîπ Real-World Example (Laptop Manufacturing)

You have a Work Order to make 50 Laptops.
According to your Routing, the first operation is ‚ÄúAssemble Components‚Äù done at Assembly Table A.

ERPNext automatically creates a Job Card for this operation.
Your technician ‚Äî say Rahul ‚Äî starts the job, records:
- Start Time and End Time
- Quantity completed (e.g., 50 Laptops assembled)
- Any downtime or remarks

After completion, this Job Card serves as a record of that operation‚Äôs work.
Then the next Job Card (for Software Installation) can begin, and so on, until all operations are completed.


‚û°Ô∏è Job Card = Work log for each operation step, tracking time, employee, and progress during Laptop manufacturing.



--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------


10. Stock Entry ( Manufacture )


üîπ Purpose / Role

- A Stock Entry of type ‚ÄúManufacture‚Äù represents the completion of the production process ‚Äî it consumes raw materials and adds the finished product to stock.
- It‚Äôs the final step in manufacturing where ERPNext updates the inventory to show that finished goods are now ready.

This entry is usually created when a Work Order is completed.



üîπ Real-World Example (Laptop Manufacturing)

After all operations (Assembly, Software Installation, Testing, Packaging) are done for 50 Laptops, you‚Äôre ready to record the finished goods.

You create a Stock Entry (Manufacture) that:

Consumes:
- 50 Motherboards
- 50 Screens
- 50 Keyboards
- 50 Batteries
- 50 Laptop Bodies

Produces:
- 50 Finished Laptops


ERPNext automatically calculates the cost of production based on consumed items and operation costs, and adds 50 Laptops to the Finished Goods Warehouse.


‚û°Ô∏è Stock Entry (Manufacture) = The final production entry that converts raw materials into finished Laptops and updates stock accordingly.





