here,
1. 
1. Allow Alternative Item
‚úîÔ∏è This allows the system to use alternative raw materials if the original item is unavailable.

--------------------

2. Use Multi-Level BOM
‚úîÔ∏è If enabled, ERPNext will plan materials not only for the final item, but also for all sub-assemblies inside the main BOM.
üìå Without this, the system uses only the top-level BOM and assumes sub-assemblies already exist.

Real-World Example:
You manufacture a bicycle.

Final bicycle BOM contains:
Frame Assembly
Wheel Assembly
Handle Assembly

Each assembly has its own BOM (multi-level).

If this option is enabled:
‚Üí ERPNext will plan raw materials for each assembly (e.g., spokes, rim, ball bearings, rods).

If disabled:
‚Üí ERPNext expects Frame Assembly, Wheel Assembly, etc. to already be in stock.


--------------------

3. Skip Material Transfer to WIP Warehouse
‚úîÔ∏è When checked, ERPNext will not require moving materials to a Work-In-Progress (WIP) warehouse before production.

üëç Useful if:
- You don't track WIP warehouses, or
- Materials go directly to the production floor.

Real-World Example:

A bakery produces bread.

They store flour, sugar, and yeast in their main warehouse.
They don't track a special "WIP Warehouse" for mixing dough.

If this option is enabled:
‚Üí Workers can directly consume flour & ingredients from the main warehouse.
‚Üí No need to do a stock entry to move materials into a WIP warehouse.

üëç So, do you still need to create Material Transfer for Manufacture?
No.

- If you enable Skip Material Transfer, you do NOT need to create a Material Transfer stock entry.

You will create only one stock entry: Manufacture

And ERPNext automatically consumes materials directly from their source warehouse.

so- > you CAN create Job Cards without Material Transfer if this option is enabled

---------------

4. Backflush Raw Materials From Work-in-Progress Warehouse
‚úîÔ∏è Automatically consumes (deducts) raw material stock only at the time of finishing the Work Order.
üîÑ You don‚Äôt need to manually create stock entries for each consumption step.
‚ö†Ô∏è Works best when your production process is simple and material usage closely matches BOM.


Real-World Example:

An electronics company is making 100 LED bulbs.

Materials needed per bulb:
- 1 LED chip
- 1 plastic body
- 2 wires

Instead of manually consuming materials each time:
- They finish production
- Submit the Work Order
- ERPNext automatically reduces raw materials based on BOM qty √ó 100 bulbs

In normal manufacturing:
- You first transfer raw materials to WIP Warehouse.
- Later ERPNext consumes (backflushes) them from the WIP Warehouse.

This option allows:
- Auto-consumption of materials already sitting in WIP Warehouse.

some error - if i do skip option then blackflush will not work because erp never consume raw materials from different warehouses if focus only one .... 
