9. Manufacturing Settings

1Ô∏è‚É£ TAB: BOM AND PRODUCTION

Raw Materials Consumption

| Field                                             | Meaning                                                                    |
| ------------------------------------------------- | -------------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| **Allow Continuous Material Consumption**         | Allow consuming raw materials even if finished goods are not yet produced. |
| **Backflush Raw Materials Based On**              | Determines how raw materials are auto-consumed (BOM or Material Transfer). |
| **Get Raw Materials Cost from Consumption Entry** | Use cost based on actual consumption entries.                              |
| **Validate Components and Quantities Per BOM**    | Enforce checking raw materials strictly against BOM.                       |

here,

1. Allow Continuous Material Consumption

by default it is off:
üëâ ERPNext will not reduce raw material stock when you start making something.
üëâ ERPNext will reduce the stock only at the moment you declare the finished item.

Raw materials are consumed gradually during production, even before the product is finished

‚úî How ERPNext behaves:
- You can create multiple Material Consumption Entries(stock entry) while production is ongoing
- Stock of raw materials goes down step-by-step
- The finished item is added to stock only at the end

üîß Stock Entries created:
- Many small Material Consumption entries
- One Finished Goods entry at the end

real world example-

A Cookie Bakery

Raw Materials:
Flour
Sugar
Butter

Finished Product:
1 Batch of Cookies

üü™ When setting is OFF (Default)
- ERPNext assumes a simple situation:
- You consume(stock changes) the ingredients only when cookies are fully baked.


Real ERPNext flow:
  1. Start Work Order ‚Üí stock unchanged
  2. Mix dough ‚Üí stock unchanged
  3. Bake ‚Üí stock unchanged
  4. Cookies finished ‚Üí ERPNext reduces flour, sugar, butter
  5. ERPNext adds batch of cookies to stock


üü© When setting is ON (Continuous Consumption)

- ERPNext assumes a more complex, realistic scenario: Ingredients are consumed as soon as you put them into the mixing bowl.

Real ERPNext flow:

1. Add flour ‚Üí ERPNext immediately reduces flour stock
2. Add sugar ‚Üí ERPNext reduces sugar stock
3. Add butter ‚Üí ERPNext reduces butter stock
4. Bake cookies
5. After baking ‚Üí ERPNext adds finished cookies to stock

note : here i need to create stock entries but ERPNext will automatically create: Finished Goods Stock Entry

-------------------------

2. Backflush Raw Materials Based On
- This decides HOW ERPNext auto-consumes(stock changes) raw materials when you finish a Work Order.( Stock Entry (Manufacture) )

A. BOM
- ERPNext will consume raw materials based only on the quantities defined in the BOM.

üßø Real-world example

BOM says:
- 5 kg flour
- 2 kg sugar
- 1 kg butter

When you finish production, ERPNext automatically consumes 5 + 2 + 1 kg exactly.
Even if you transferred more or less, ERPNext still uses BOM values.

‚úî When choosing BOM:
- Raw materials are consumed automatically when the Work Order is completed.
- ERPNext looks at the BOM and deducts materials exactly as listed.
- No need for Material Transfer entries.


B. Material Transfer
- ERPNext will consume raw materials based on the quantities you actually transferred to the Work Order, not the BOM.

üßø Real-world example

You transferred:
12 kg flour
3 kg sugar

Even if the BOM says flour = 10 kg, ERPNext will consume 12 kg because that‚Äôs what was transferred.


‚úî When choosing Material Transfer:
- ERPNext waits for your ‚ÄúMaterial Transfer for Manufacture‚Äù stock entries.
- Whatever quantity you transferred ‚Üí ERPNext consumes that exact amount.
- If you transferred 12 kg instead of 10 kg, ERPNext consumes 12 kg.


-------------------------

3. Get Raw Materials Cost from Consumption Entry ( open if you choose Allow Continuous Material Consumption )

- ERPNext will calculate the cost of finished goods based on the actual material consumption entries you made, not based on " BOM ".

üè≠ Real-World Example
You make 100 T-shirts

BOM says:
2 meters cloth per shirt
Total: 200 meters cloth

But in real production:
- Workers consumed 210 meters cloth (10 meters wasted)

- You created Material Consumption entries showing 210 meters used.

‚úî If Setting is ON
ERPNext uses 210 meters cost to value finished goods.
This shows real cost, including wastage.

‚úò If Setting is OFF
ERPNext ignores real consumption.
It uses 200 meters from BOM, even though you consumed more.


-------------------------


4. Validate Components and Quantities Per BOM
- controls whether ERPNext should strictly enforce that all raw materials (components) and their quantities match the Bill of Materials (BOM) whenever you create:
  Work Orders
  Stock Entries (Manufacture / Repack)
  Production Planning
  Subassemblies 
  ....

‚úÖ What this setting does

When enabled:

1. Only the exact items listed in the BOM can be used. You cannot add extra raw materials or remove any BOM item.

2. Quantities must match the BOM, unless you explicitly change the BOM or set tolerances.
-  If your Stock Entry uses more or less than the BOM quantity, ERPNext will throw a validation error.

3. Prevents accidental mistakes like:
- Using the wrong component
- Using incorrect qty
- Producing using an outdated BOM

It enforces strict BOM compliance for controlled manufacturing environments.


‚ùå When disabled :

You are allowed to:
- Add materials not listed in the BOM
- Change quantities freely
- Ignore mismatches between BOM and stock entry / work order consumption

Good for flexible or manual production processes.




BOM

| Field                             | Meaning                                                     |
| --------------------------------- | ----------------------------------------------------------- |
| **Update BOM Cost Automatically** | Scheduler updates BOM cost using latest material valuation. |

here,

1. Update BOM Cost Automatically
- When this option is enabled, ERPNext will automatically recalculate (update) the cost of all Bill of Materials (BOMs) whenever the following change:
   - Item price changes (valuation rate)
   - Raw material cost updates
   - Sub-assemblies‚Äô BOM costs change
   - A user manually triggers a BOM update


‚úîÔ∏è What Happens Internally

If enabled, ERPNext will:
- Fetch the latest cost of each raw material (based on valuation rate or price list).
- Recalculate the Total Cost and Per Unit Cost of the BOM.
- Save the updated cost back to the BOM automatically.

This ensures manufacturing costing stays accurate without needing to manually click "Update Cost" on every BOM.




Default Warehouses for Production

| Field                                  | Meaning                                  |
| -------------------------------------- | ---------------------------------------- |
| **Default Work In Progress Warehouse** | Default warehouse for WIP items.         |
| **Default Finished Goods Warehouse**   | Default warehouse for finished products. |
| **Default Scrap Warehouse**            | Default warehouse for storing scrap.     |




Overproduction for Sales and Work Order

| Field                                         | Meaning                                                    |
| --------------------------------------------- | ---------------------------------------------------------- |
| **Overproduction Percentage For Sales Order** | Allowed extra production percentage above sales order qty. |
| **Overproduction Percentage For Work Order**  | Allowed extra production percentage above work order qty.  |

here,

ex. 

Sales Order Qty = 100 pcs
Overproduction Percentage = 10%
Allowed Production Qty = 100 + 10% = 110 pcs

&

Work Order Qty: 200 units
Overproduction % for Work Order: 8%
Allowed Qty to Produce: 200 √ó 1.08 = 216 units


2Ô∏è‚É£ TAB: JOB CARD AND CAPACITY PLANNING


Job Card Settings

| Field                                                        | Meaning                                       |
| ------------------------------------------------------------ | --------------------------------------------- |
| **Add Corrective Operation Cost in Finished Good Valuation** | Add cost of corrective operations in FG cost. |
| **Enforce Time Logs**                                        | Force job card to have From Time and To Time. |

here,

1. Add Corrective Operation Cost in Finished Good Valuation
During manufacturing, a Work Order includes:

Raw Materials cost
- Operation cost (from Workstations / Operation rates)
- Additional expenses

Sometimes, during the process, the actual operation cost ends up higher or lower than what was originally estimated.
- These differences are called Corrective Operation Costs.

If ‚ÄúAdd Corrective Operation Cost in Finished Good Valuation‚Äù is enabled:
‚Üí ERPNext includes these corrected (actual) operation costs into the final valuation of the finished goods.

If disabled:
‚Üí ERPNext ignores the corrected operation costs and only uses the originally estimated operation rates for valuation.

-------------------------

2. Enforce Time Logs

When this setting is enabled, ERPNext forces users to create Time Logs for each operation performed in a Work Order.
This ensures actual machine/labor time is captured before the operation can be marked complete.

In short:
You cannot complete manufacturing operations without entering Time Logs.

‚úîÔ∏è What Happens When It Is ENABLED
ERPNext requires:
- Job Cards ‚Üí Time Log entry
- Actual Start Time / End Time
- Operation hours
- Optional: Machine, employee, workstation



Material Transfer

| Field                              | Meaning                                                       |
| ---------------------------------- | ------------------------------------------------------------- |
| **Allow Excess Material Transfer** | Allow transferring more raw materials than required quantity. |

here,

1. Allow Excess Material Transfer 
- Every Work Order calculates the required quantity of raw materials based on the BOM.

Example:
If the BOM requires 10 kg of a material, ERPNext expects exactly 10 kg to be transferred from the warehouse to WIP.

When Allow Excess Material Transfer = ON:
‚Üí You can transfer more than the required quantity, such as 11 kg, 12 kg, etc.
ERPNext will NOT block the transfer.

When Allow Excess Material Transfer = OFF:
‚Üí ERPNext will block transfers that exceed the Work Order requirement.
You will see an error like: ‚ÄúTransferred quantity cannot exceed required quantity.‚Äù



Capacity Planning

| Field                              | Meaning                                                |
| ---------------------------------- | ------------------------------------------------------ |
| **Disable Capacity Planning**      | Turn off workstation capacity planning.                |
| **Allow Overtime**                 | Allow planning work outside workstation working hours. |
| **Allow Production on Holidays**   | Allow scheduling production on holidays.               |
| **Capacity Planning For (Days)**   | Number of days to plan manufacturing operations ahead. |
| **Time Between Operations (Mins)** | Time gap between sequential operations.                |

here,

1. Disable Capacity Planning

When Disable Capacity Planning = ON

ERPNext IGNORES:
- Workstation capacity (e.g., machine hours per day)
- Operation scheduling
- Overlaps or overbooking of machines
- Production load on workstations

Work Orders can be created and scheduled freely without any capacity checks.

‚û°Ô∏è In simple words: No scheduling ‚Üí No capacity limits ‚Üí Just create Work Orders anytime.


When Disable Capacity Planning = OFF (capacity planning is enabled)

ERPNext will:
- Check available machine hours
- Prevent scheduling beyond available capacity
- Schedule operations in a Gantt chart or timeline
- Ensure operations don‚Äôt overlap when not allowed
- Follow workstation timing rules (e.g., 8 hours/day)

If a machine/workstation is fully booked, ERPNext shows errors like: ‚ÄúNot enough capacity on Workstation ‚ÄòX‚Äô for this operation.‚Äù

-------------------------

2. Allow Overtime

Each Workstation has defined:
- Working Hours per Day (e.g., 8 hours/day)
- A Holiday List
- Capacity planning rules

When ERPNext schedules production, it normally cannot exceed those working hours.

If Allow Overtime = ON ‚Üí ERPNext can schedule more than the defined capacity.
If Allow Overtime = OFF ‚Üí ERPNext blocks or reschedules any production that exceeds available hours.


‚úîÔ∏è Example to Understand
Workstation Capacity:
- Working Hours: 8 hours/day

Operation Requirement for a Work Order:
- Required: 10 hours

üîπ If Allow Overtime = OFF
ERPNext schedules:
- Day 1 ‚Üí 8 hrs
- Day 2 ‚Üí 2 hrs

Because ERPNext cannot exceed daily capacity.

üîπ If Allow Overtime = ON
- ERPNext schedules everything in one day, even though 10 hrs > 8 hrs.

Meaning:
‚úî Work Order fully scheduled in 1 day
‚úî Machine is considered to work overtime
‚úî No splitting into multiple days


-------------------------


3. Allow Production on Holidays
- Every Workstation in ERPNext has a Holiday List (e.g., Sundays, national holidays, shutdown days).

Normally, ERPNext will avoid scheduling production on those holiday dates.

Allow Production on Holidays = ON -> ERPNext can schedule operations even on holiday dates.
Allow Production on Holidays = OFF -> ERPNext prevents operations from being scheduled on holidays.


-------------------------


4. Capacity Planning For (Days)
-  ERPNext will plan and schedule your production only for the next X days

Example:

If you set Capacity Planning For = 30 days
ERPNext plans and schedules production 30 days into the future.

If you set Capacity Planning For = 7 days
ERPNext only schedules production for one week ahead.


‚úîÔ∏è Example Scenario
Assume:
- Workstation: 8 hrs/day
- Required operation time: 40 hours


üîπ Capacity Planning For = 3 days
Planning window = 3 days
Available hours = 8 * 3 = 24 hrs

‚û°Ô∏è ERPNext will only schedule 24 hours worth of operations
‚û°Ô∏è Remaining 16 hours will not be scheduled (or ERPNext will throw a capacity conflict error)

üîπ Capacity Planning For = 10 days
Available hours = 8 * 10 = 80 hrs

‚û°Ô∏è ERPNext can easily fit the 40-hour job
‚û°Ô∏è Schedules it properly over several days

‚úîÔ∏è In Simple Words

| Setting                     | Meaning                      |
| --------------------------- | ---------------------------- |
| **Small number (5‚Äì7 days)** | Short-term scheduling window |
| **Medium (15‚Äì30 days)**     | Normal production planning   |
| **Large (60‚Äì90 days)**      | Long-term factory scheduling |


‚úîÔ∏è When Should You Change This?
Set LOW value (e.g., 7‚Äì14 days) if:
- Your production changes frequently
- You want short-term flexible schedules
- You have dynamic orders

Set HIGH value (30+ days) if:
- You have long Work Orders
- You plan production monthly or quarterly
- You want to schedule long projects in advance


note :
- to schedule remaining days, to complete work order you need to change this days(mention in Capacity Planning For (Days)), erpnext not allow  automatically schedule that work ..

-------------------------

5. Time Between Operations (Mins) 
- This is the waiting time between two operations in a Work Order.

Example:
- Operation 1 finishes at 10:00 AM
- Time Between Operations = 30 minutes
- Operation 2 will be scheduled to start at 10:30 AM

If you set:
- Time Between Operations = 15 minutes
- Then every operation in the Work Order will have a 15-minute gap before the next one starts.

note :
- this is just for planning, you can still create job card for that operation if gap is not full filled. 








Other Settings

| Field                                                    | Meaning                                                                      |
| -------------------------------------------------------- | ---------------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| **Set Operating Cost / Scrap Items From Sub-assemblies** | Include sub-assembly costs/scrap in finished goods without using a job card. |
| **Make Serial No / Batch from Work Order**               | Auto-generate serial/batch numbers when work order is submitted.             |

here,

1. Set Operating Cost / Scrap Items From Sub-assemblies
- This setting tells ERPNext: 
            When a BOM has sub-assemblies, should ERPNext also include their operating cost and scrap items in the final calculation?

‚úîÔ∏è Breaking It Down
üîπ 1. Sub-assemblies
- These are BOMs inside another BOM.
Example:

Main Product BOM
‚îî‚îÄ‚îÄ Sub-Assembly A BOM
‚îî‚îÄ‚îÄ Sub-Assembly B BOM

Each sub-assembly may have:
- Operating cost (machine/labor)
- Scrap items


‚úî When ENABLED (ON)
- ERPNext will pull operating cost and scrap items of sub-assemblies into the main BOM / main Work Order.

Meaning:
- Sub-assembly operation cost is added to final cost
- Scrap generated in sub-assembly is included
- Your costing becomes fully accurate

Example

Sub-assembly has:
- Operating cost = 50
- Scrap = 2 kg

Main BOM will now include:
+50 operating cost
+2 kg scrap


‚ùå When DISABLED (OFF)
- ERPNext ignores the operating cost and scrap of sub-assemblies.

Meaning:
- Only direct BOM operations & scrap are counted
- Sub-assembly costs are NOT included
- Costing becomes simpler but maybe less accurate

-------------------------

2. Make Serial No / Batch from Work Order
- This setting tells ERPNext:
        Automatically create Serial Numbers or Batch Numbers for the finished goods when you complete a Work Order.


‚úîÔ∏è Why This Matters
- Many factories produce items that must have:
Serial Numbers (unique per piece)
Batch Numbers (group of pieces made together)

ERPNext can create these automatically during manufacturing if this setting is ON.


‚úîÔ∏è What Happens When Setting is ON
When you complete a Work Order:
- ERPNext will generate Serial Numbers (if the item is serialized)
- ERPNext will generate a Batch Number (if the item is batched)

You don‚Äôt need to manually create them.


Example:

Finished Item: ‚ÄúPump Motor‚Äù
Item has Serial Number Required = Yes

Work Order produces 10 units
‚û°Ô∏è ERPNext automatically creates 10 serial numbers
‚û°Ô∏è They get assigned to the finished goods stock entry

(Same for Batch items)


‚úîÔ∏è What Happens When Setting is OFF
- ERPNext will NOT create serial or batch numbers automatically.

You must:
- create Batch manually
- or create Serial Numbers manually
- or select an existing Batch

If you forget ‚Üí ERPNext blocks the stock entry.


‚úîÔ∏è Ultra Simple Examples
‚úî When ON: Produce 100 bottles ‚Üí system creates a new Batch without asking you.
‚úî When OFF: You must choose or create the Batch manually before submitting.


‚≠ê Summary (Very Simple)

ON = ERPNext auto-creates Serial/Batch numbers when finishing Work Order.
OFF = You must create them manually.


note : 
1. To use ‚ÄúMake Serial No / Batch from Work Order‚Äù, your item must already be marked as:

   Has Serial No ‚Üí if the item needs serial numbers
   Has Batch No ‚Üí if the item needs batch numbers

Otherwise ERPNext cannot create serial or batch numbers automatically.



################################################ END



stock entries :

‚úîÔ∏è Material Transfer = just moving items, NOT consuming
‚úîÔ∏è Manufacture = consuming materials + creating finished goods


work order main cycel :: start ->  job crad -> finish

